{"title_page": "Eric Allan Kramer", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Eric Allan Kramer\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_place        = [[Grand Rapids]], [[Michigan]], US\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1962|03|26}}\n| years_active       = 1987\u2013present\n| occupation         = Actor, fight choreographer\n| nationality        = American\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Alberta]] ([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]])\n| residence          = \n| spouse             = Unknown\n}} \n\n'''Eric Allan Kramer''' (born March 26, 1962)<ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/2012/07/27/good-luck-star-muscles-up Good Luck\u2019 star muscles up]</ref> is an [[United States|American]]  [[character actor]] who has appeared in numerous [[feature film]]s and [[Television program|television programs]] including ''[[True Romance]]'' and ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]],'' but is best known for his role as Dave Rogers on ''[[The Hughleys]]'' and Bob Duncan on ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'' from 2010\u20132014. He also appeared as Iron Mike Wilcox in the 2019 video game ''[[Days Gone]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nKramer's father, [[Roger Kramer]], is a former [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] player. Kramer attended the [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]] program at the [[University of Alberta]] in [[Edmonton]], which led to acting in the theater and some television and movie roles, as well as a career in [[fight choreography]].<ref>[http://www.wchstv.com/abc/hughleys/ericallankramer.shtml Eric Allan Kramer ABC bio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303035142/http://www.wchstv.com/abc/hughleys/ericallankramer.shtml |date=March 3, 2007 }} from ''The Hughleys''</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1987, Kramer made his acting debut in television film ''[[The Gunfighters (1987 film)|The Gunfighters]]''. He also starred in the 1990 film ''[[Quest for the Mighty Sword]],''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.badmovieplanet.com/unknownmovies/reviews/rev68.html |title=The Unknown Movies \u2013 ''Quest For The Mighty Sword'' (1989) |access-date=February 7, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406223007/http://www.badmovieplanet.com/unknownmovies/reviews/rev68.html |archive-date=April 6, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> replacing previous lead actor [[Miles O'Keeffe]]. He played [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]] in NBC's television film ''[[The Incredible Hulk Returns]]'' and a Russian baseball player in the television movie ''The Comrades of Summer''. Among Kramer's more notable roles have been Little John in ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]'', Bear in ''[[American Wedding]]'', and Boris, bodyguard to producer Lee Donowitz, in ''[[True Romance]]''. He has also appeared in a number of notable television series, including ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'', ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'', ''[[Growing Pains]]'', ''[[Cheers]]'', ''[[Empty Nest (TV series)|Empty Nest]]'', ''[[Blossom (TV series)|Blossom]]'', ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', ''[[NewsRadio]]'', ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'', ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'', ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[That '70s Show]]'', ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'', ''[[Monk (TV series)|Monk]]'', ''[[Jack and Bobby]]'', ''[[Phil of the Future]]'', ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', ''[[The King of Queens]]'', ''[[My Name Is Earl]]'', and ''[[Will and Grace]]'' (where he was in the same episode as his ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'' wife [[Leigh-Allyn Baker]]). Kramer was also a series regular on the sitcom ''[[Bob (TV series)|Bob]]'' as Whitey van de Bunt (1993) and the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]/[[UPN]] sitcom ''[[The Hughleys]]'' as Dave Rogers.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/75/Eric-Allan-Kramer.html Eric Allan Kramer Biography ((?)-)], Film Reference</ref>\n\nKramer continues to work on the stage as a member of the Antaeus Classical Rep Company in Los Angeles and received an Ovatti Award nomination for his role in [[The Wood Demon (play)|''The Wood Demon'']]. He also co-starred as Bob Duncan on the [[Disney Channel]] sitcom ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]''. He also played Link's dad in the [[Nickelodeon]] series ''[[The Thundermans]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!| Year\n!| Title\n!| Role\n!| Notes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Quest for the Mighty Sword]]''\n| Ator\n| [[Direct-to-video]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1993\n| ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]''\n| Little John\n|\n|-\n| ''[[True Romance]]''\n| Boris\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Road to Saddle River]]''\n| Dieter\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''The Crazysitter''\n| Elliot\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[High School High]]''\n| Hulk\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[American Wedding]]''\n| Bear\n| \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Grilled (film)|Grilled]]\n| Irving\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Flying By]]''\n| Steve\n| Direct-to-video\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Meat and Potatoes''\n| Bill\n| [[Short film]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2014\n| ''[[Atlas Shrugged Part III: Who Is John Galt?]]''\n| Ragnar Danneskj\u00f6ld\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mostly Ghostly: Have You Met My Ghoulfriend?]]''\n| John Doyle\n|\n|-\n| ''The Mundane Goddess''\n| Zeus\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''LA Apocalypse''\n| Sergeant Wade\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2016\n| ''8989 Redstone''\n| Daryl Masters\n|\n|-\n| ''Surge of Power: Revenge of the Sequel''\n| Moon\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Pitching Tents''\n| Bruce\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!| Year\n!| Title\n!| Role\n!| Notes\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[The Gunfighters (1987 film)|The Gunfighters]]''\n| Luke Collins\n| TV movie\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1988\n| ''[[The Incredible Hulk Returns]]''\n| [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]]\n| TV movie\n|-\n| ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''\n| Gunnar Tilstrom\n| Episode: \"Snow White, Blood Red\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1989\n| ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]''\n| Bobo\n| Episode: \"Dan's Birthday Bash\"\n|-\n| ''[[Growing Pains]]''\n| Tony\n| Episode: \"Feet of Clay\"\n|-\n| ''[[Cheers]]''\n| 