tabase.com/waterfall/Hidden-Falls-695|title=Hidden Falls, China \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n|-\n! 21\n| [[San Rafael Falls]]\n| [[File:AMA Cascada de San Rafael limite provincial de Napo y Sucumb\u00edos (8227381138).jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|00400|400}}\n| 94\n| 23\n| [[Coca River|Coca]]\n| {{flag|Ecuador}}\n| {{coord|-0.104303|-77.580967|format=dms|name=San Rafael Falls (former)}}\n| On 2 February 2020, the waterfall disappeared after a large [[sinkhole]] formed just above the falls, diverting its flow into three gradually sloping cataracts beneath the large rock arch that survived the collapse. As a result, all tourism to the site was closed. The cause of the sinkhole is still being investigated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mongabay.com/2020/03/why-did-ecuadors-tallest-waterfall-suddenly-disappear/|title=Why did Ecuador\u2019s tallest waterfall suddenly disappear?|date=2020-03-18|website=Mongabay Environmental News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146502/the-disappearance-of-ecuadors-tallest-waterfall|title=The Disappearance of Ecuador\u2019s Tallest Waterfall|date=2020-03-27|website=earthobservatory.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/San-Rafael-Cascada-de-373|title=San Rafael, Cascada de, Ecuador \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n|-\n! 22\n| [[Urri\u00f0afoss]]\n| [[File:Urri\u00f0afoss2009.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|00360|360}}\n| 4\n| 229\n| [[\u00dej\u00f3rs\u00e1]]\n| {{flag|Iceland}}\n| {{coord|63.92506|-20.672678|format=dms|name=Urri\u00f0afoss}}\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Urrithafoss-14805|title=Urri\u00f0afoss, Iceland \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.co