ttifoss]]\n| [[File:Dettifoss TimBekaert.JPG|100px]]\n| {{sort|00269|269}}\n| 51\n| 171\n| [[J\u00f6kuls\u00e1 \u00e1 Fj\u00f6llum]]\n| {{flag|Iceland}}\n| {{coord|65.8146330|-16.3843220|format=dms|name=Dettifoss}}\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Dettifoss-119|title=Dettifoss, Iceland \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n|-\n! 27\n| [[Hafragilsfoss]]\n| [[File:Hafragilsfoss-2006-burras.de.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|00269|269}}\n| 27\n| 85\n| [[J\u00f6kuls\u00e1 \u00e1 Fj\u00f6llum]]\n| {{flag|Iceland}}\n| {{coord|65.8322810|-16.3991539|format=dms|name=Hafragilsfoss}}\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Hafragilsfoss-658|title=Hafragilsfoss, Iceland \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n|-\n! 27\n| [[Selfoss (waterfall)|Selfoss]]\n| [[File:IJsland Selfoss woaterval.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|00269|269}}\n| 13\n| 387\n| [[J\u00f6kuls\u00e1 \u00e1 Fj\u00f6llum]]\n| {{flag|Iceland}}\n| {{coord|65.80495|-16.38657|format=dms|name=Selfoss}}\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Selfoss-659|title=Selfoss, Iceland \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n|-\n! 27\n| [[R\u00e9ttarfoss]]\n| [[File:Aerial View of R\u00e9ttarfoss 21.05.2008 15-49-46.JPG|100px]]\n| {{sort|00269|269}}\n| ?\n| ?\n| [[J\u00f6kuls\u00e1 \u00e1 Fj\u00f6llum]]\n| {{flag|Iceland}}\n| {{coord|65.879645|-16.435802|format=dms|name=R\u00e9ttarfoss}}\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Rettarfoss-14669|title=R\u00e9ttarfoss, Iceland \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThe first five waterfalls by power (Gua\u00edra, Khone Phapheng, Iguaz\u00fa, Niagara, and Victoria) are called the ''Great Five Waterfalls''.<ref>\u0413. \u0422. \u0410\u0440\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432. \u0412\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0434\u044b. \u2014 \u041c.: \u041c\u044b\u0441\u043b\u044c, 1987. \u2014 \u0421. 14. \u2014 127 \u0441.</ref><ref>\u0412. \u0418. \u0417\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0439, \u041a. \u0412. \u0417\u0432\u043e\u0440\u044b\u043a\u0438\u043d. \u041c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a\u043e-\u0433\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f. \u2014 \u041c.: \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420, 1975. \u2014 \u0421. 60. \u2014 78 \u0441.</ref>\n\n==Prehistoric waterfalls==\n{{see also|Outburst flood}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Waterfall!!Maximum daily flow rate (m<sup>3</sup>/s)!!Tallest single drop (m) !! Width (m)!!River!!Countries\n|-\n|[[Strait of Gibraltar|Gibraltar]] ([[Zanclean flood|Zanclean deluge hypothesis]])||{{sort|20000000000000|2\u00d710<sup>13</sup>}}<ref name=\"GCetal2009\">Garcia-Castellanos, D., Estrada, F., Jim\u00e9nez-Munt, I., Gorini, C., Fern\u00e0ndez, M., Verg\u00e9s, J., De Vicente, R. (10 December 2009) [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v462/n7274/full/nature08555.html Catastrophic flood of the Mediterranean after the Messinian salinity crisis], ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' 462, pp. 778\u2013781, {{DOI|10.1038/nature08555}}</ref>||{{sort|1000|>&nbsp;1000}}||||[[Strait of Gibraltar]] || {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Spain]]<br>{{flagicon|Morocco}} [[Morocco]]\n|-\n|[[Dry Falls]]||{{sort|1906000|1,906,000}}<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/geology/publications/inf/72-2/sec5.htm|title=The Channeled Scablands of Eastern Washington|publisher=United States Geological Survey|accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref>||{{sort|350|350}}||{{sort|4828|4,828}}||[[Columbia river|Columbia]]||{{Flagicon|United States}} [[United States]]\n|-\n|[[Bosphorus Strait|Bosphorus]] ([[Black Sea deluge hypothesis]])||{{sort|0482407|482,407}}<ref>Ryan, W.B.F.; Pitman III, W.C., ''et al.'' 1997. An abrupt drowning of the Black Sea shelf. ''Marine Geology'', 138: 119\u2013126.</ref>||{{sort|080|80}}||||[[Bosphorus Strait]]||{{Flagicon|Turkey}} [[Turkey]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Waterfall]]\n*[[List of rivers by discharge]]\n*[[List of waterfalls]]\n*[[List of waterfalls by height]]\n*[[List of waterfalls by type]]\n*[[Orders of magnitude (power)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/ World Waterfall Database]\n\n{{Great Five Waterfalls}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of waterfalls|Flow rate]]\n", "text_old": "This '''list of waterfalls by flow rate in the world''' includes waterfalls that have an average [[Volumetric flow rate|flow rate]] greater than {{convert|250|m3|ft3}}. This list is sorted by mean annual flow rate of the [[waterfall]] by default, but can also be sorted by other criteria, such as width, power, etc.\n\n==Largest waterfalls by flow rate==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Rank\n! Waterfall\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n! {{abbr|Average flow rate|Average annual flow rate}} (m<sup>3</sup>/s)\n! {{abbr|Tallest drop|Tallest single drop}} (m)\n! Average width (m)\n! River\n! Countries\n! Coordinates\n! Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\"|{{abbr|Ref|References}}\n|-\n! 1\n| [[Inga Falls]]\n| [[File:Inga03.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|25768|25,768}} ({{abbr|est.|Estimation}})\n| 21\n| 914\n| [[Congo River|Congo]]\n| {{flag|DRC}}\n| {{coord|-5.448835|13.588362|format=dms|name=Inga Falls}}\n| The Inga falls, whose status as a true waterfall is controversial, are currently incorporated into the Inga I and Inga II hydroelectric facilities. The volume of the river diverted is approximately 30% of the average discharge. The [[Grand Inga Dam]], potentially the world's largest by generating capacity, is also proposed to be built on the falls.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Inga-Falls-660|title=Inga Falls, Congo, Democratic Republic of the \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 2\n| [[Livingstone Falls]]\n| [[File:Chutes Livingstone.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|25060|25,060}}\n| 6\n| 701\n| [[Congo River|Congo]]\n| {{flag|DRC}}<br>{{flag|Republic of the Congo}}<br>\n| {{coord|-4.878146|14.435622|format=dms|name=Livingstone Falls}}\n| A set of rapids that drops {{Convert|6|m||abbr=}}. Located at the southern end of the [[Republic of the Congo]]'s border with the Congo River.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Livingstone-Chutes-de-104|title=Livingstone, Chutes de, Congo, Democratic Republic of the \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 3\n| [[Boyoma Falls]]\n| [[File:Zaire kisangani stroom 12 copy (cropped).jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|16990|16,990}}\n| 5\n| 1,372\n| [[Lualaba River|Lualaba]], [[Congo River|Congo]]\n| {{flag|DRC}}\n| {{coord|0.49091096|25.20680491|format=dms|name=Boyoma Falls}}\n|A series of seven cataracts, also referred to as the Stanley Falls. The last and most significant of these cataracts, at [[Kisangani]], is known as Wagenia.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ndeo|first=Oscar|last2=Hauffe|first2=Torsten|last3=Delicado|first3=Diana|last4=Busanga|first4=Alidor|last5=Albrecht|first5=Christian|date=2017-05-02|title=Mollusk communities of the central Congo River shaped by combined effects of barriers, environmental gradients, and species dispersal|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/316971348_Mollusk_communities_of_the_central_Congo_River_shaped_by_combined_effects_of_barriers_environmental_gradients_and_species_dispersal|journal=Journal of Limnology|volume=76|doi=10.4081/jlimnol.2017.1585}}</ref> The Boyoma Falls marks the transition to the [[Congo River]] from the [[Lualaba River]].\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Wagenia-Chutes-102|title=Wagenia, Chutes, Congo, Democratic Republic of the \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|- \n! -\n| [[Gua\u00edra Falls]] (submerged)\n| [[File:Salto das Sete Quedas.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|13309|13,309}}\n| 40\n| 4,828\n| [[Paran\u00e1 River|Paran\u00e1]]\n| {{flag|Brazil}}<br>{{flag|Paraguay}}\n| {{coord|-24.067547|-54.283276|format=dms|name=Gua\u00edra Falls (submerged)}}\n| Submerged beneath the [[Itaipu Dam|Itaipu Reservoir]] following the completion of the [[Itaipu Dam]] in 1982. The falls were later dynamited by the Brazilian government to promote safer navigation on the river.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Gua%C3%ADra-Salto-del-103|title=Gua\u00edra, Salto del, Brazil \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 4\n| [[Khone Phapheng Falls]]\n| [[File:Khone Phapheng Falls - 1.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|11610|11,610}}\n| 21\n| 10,783\n| [[Mekong River|Mekong]]\n| {{flag|Laos}}\n| {{coord|13.9549940|105.9027541|format=dms|name=Khone Phapheng Falls}}\n| A series of falls and rapids that when measured end-to-end is over 10 kilometres in width, making it the world's widest waterfall. Largest waterfall in [[Asia]] by average flow rate.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Khone-Chutes-de-105|title=Khone, Chutes de, Laos \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|- \n! -\n| [[Celilo Falls]] (submerged)\n| [[File:Corps-engineers-archives celilo falls color.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|05366|5,366}}\n| ?\n| 1,768\n| [[Columbia River|Columbia]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| {{coord|45.65147|-120.96941|format=dms|name=Celilo Falls (submerged)}}\n| Submerged beneath the [[Columbia River]] following the completion of [[The Dalles Dam]] in 1957. The falls remain intact.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Celilo-Falls-5475|title=Celilo Falls, Oregon, United States \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|- \n! -\n| [[Kettle Falls]] (submerged)\n| [[File:Kettlefalls.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|04682|4,682}}\n| ?\n| ?\n| [[Columbia River|Columbia]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| {{coord|48.63099|-118.11897|format=dms|name=Kettle Falls (submerged)}}\n| Submerged beneath [[Franklin D. Roosevelt Lake|Lake Roosevelt]] following the completion of the [[Grand Coulee Dam]] in 1940. The falls remain intact.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Kettle-Falls-9526|title=Kettle Falls, Washington, United States \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 5\n| [[Par\u00e1 Falls]]\n| [[File:Salto Para.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|03540|3,540}}\n| ?\n| 5,608\n| [[Caura River (Venezuela)|Caura]]\n| {{flag|Bolivia}}<br>{{flag|Venezuela}}\n| {{coord|6.31699585|-64.5090696|format=dms|name=Salto P\u00e1ra}}\n| Largest extant waterfall in [[South America]] by average flow rate.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Para-Salto-687|title=Par\u00e1, Salto, Venezuela \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 6\n| [[Paulo Afonso Falls]]\n| [[File:Cachoeira de Paulo Afonso BA.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|02832|2,832}}\n| 59\n| 18\n| [[S\u00e3o Francisco River|S\u00e3o Francisco]]\n| {{flag|Brazil}}\n| {{coord|-9.3890899|-38.1957704|format=dms|name=Paulo Afonso Falls}}\n| In 1948, the river was [[Paulo Afonso Hydroelectric Complex|dammed]] upstream from the falls, drastically reducing its average flow rate. The falls act as a spillway during high rainfall years.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Paulo-Afonso-Cachoeira-de-107|title=Paulo Afonso, Cachoeira de, Brazil \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|- \n! -\n| [[Urubupunga Falls]] (submerged)\n| \n| {{sort|02747|2,747}}\n| 13\n| 2,012\n| [[Paran\u00e1 River|Paran\u00e1]]\n| {{flag|Brazil}}\n| {{coord|-20.6|-51.55|format=dms|name=Salto do Urubupunga}}\n| Submerged beneath the [[Paran\u00e1 River]] following completion of the [[Engineer Souza Dias Dam]] in 1982. The falls remain intact.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Urubupunga-Salto-do-108|title=Urubupunga, Salto do, Brazil \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 7\n| [[Niagara Falls]]\n| [[File:Canadian Horseshoe Falls with city of Niagara Falls, Ontario in background.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|02407|2,407}}\n| 51\n| 1,204\n| [[Niagara River|Niagara]]\n| {{flag|Canada}}<br>{{flag|United States}}\n| {{coord|43.08|-79.071|format=dms|name=Niagara Falls}}\n| Largest extant waterfall in [[North America]] by average flow rate.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Niagara-Falls-106|title=Niagara Falls, Ontario, Canada \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 8\n| [[Vermilion Falls]]\n| [[File:A scow transitting the Vermilion Chutes.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|01812|1,812}}\n| 5\n| 1,829\n| [[Peace River|Peace]]\n| {{flag|Canada}}\n| {{coord|58.3697239|-114.871761|format=dms|name=Vermilion Falls}}\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Vermilion-Falls-2686|title=Vermilion Falls, Alberta, Canada \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 9\n| [[Iguaz\u00fa Falls]]\n| [[File:Cataratas.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|01746|1,746}}\n| 64\n| 2,682\n| [[Iguaz\u00fa River|Iguaz\u00fa]]\n| {{flag|Argentina}}<br>{{flag|Brazil}}\n| {{coord|-25.695277|-54.43667|format=dms|name=Iguaz\u00fa Falls}}\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Iguazu-Cataratas-del-109|title=Iguaz\u00fa, Cataratas del, Argentina \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|- \n! -\n| [[Maribondo Falls]] (submerged) \n| \n| {{sort|01501|1,501}}\n| 24\n| 2,012\n| [[Rio Grande (Paran\u00e1 River)|Rio Grande]]\n| {{flag|Brazil}}\n| {{coord|-20.314284|-49.193689|format=dms|name=Saltos dos Patos e Maribondo}}\n| Partially flooded over by the [[Marimbondo Dam|Maribondo Dam]] built on top of half the falls. The bottom of part of the dewatered falls is visible to one side of the dam.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Patos-e-Maribondo-Saltos-dos-110|title=Patos e Maribondo, Saltos dos, Brazil \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 10\n| [[Victoria Falls]]\n| [[File:Victoriaf\u00e4lle.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sort|01088|1,088}}\n| 105\n| 1,707\n| [[Zambezi River|Zambezi]]\n|{{flag|Zambia}}{{flag|Zimbabwe}}\n| {{coord|-17.924028|25.856083|format=dms|name=Victoria Falls}}\n| Produces the largest sheet of falling water in the world.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Victoria-Falls-111|title=Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe \u2013 World Waterfall Database|website=www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n! 11\n| [[Virginia Falls (Northwest Territories)|Virginia Falls]]\n| [[File:Nahanni 